# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: snmp
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:snmp/management-information-base] A **management information base** (**MIB**) is a database used for managing the entities in a communication network.
[src:snmp/management-information-base] Most often associated with the Simple Network Management Protocol (SNMP), the term is also used more generically in contexts such as in OSI/ISO Network management model.
[src:snmp/management-information-base] While intended to refer to the complete collection of management information available on an entity, it is often used to refer to a particular subset, more correctly referred to as a MIB module.
[src:snmp/management-information-base] Objects in the MIB are defined using a subset of Abstract Syntax Notation One (ASN.1) called "Structure of Management Information Version 2 (SMIv2)" RFC 2578.
[src:snmp/management-information-base] The software that performs the parsing is a MIB compiler.
[src:snmp/management-information-base] The database is hierarchical (tree-structured) and each entry is addressed through an object identifier (OID).
[src:snmp/management-information-base] Abstract Syntax Notation One (ASN.1) is a standard and flexible notation that describes data structures for representing, encoding, transmitting, and decoding data.
[src:snmp/management-information-base] It provides a set of formal rules for describing the structure of objects that are independent of machine-specific encoding techniques and is a precise, formal notation that removes ambiguities.
[src:snmp/management-information-base] ASN.1 is a joint ISO and ITU-T standard, originally defined in 1984 as part of CCITT X.409:1984.
[src:snmp/management-information-base] ASN.1 moved to its own standard, X.208, in 1988 due to its broader applicability.
[src:snmp/management-information-base] The substantially revised 1995 version is covered by the X.680 standards series.
[src:snmp/management-information-base] An adapted subset of ASN.1, Structure of Management Information (SMI), is specified for use in SNMP to define sets of related MIB objects; these sets are termed MIB modules.
[src:snmp/management-information-base] The MIB hierarchy can be depicted as a tree with a nameless root, the levels of which are assigned by different organizations.
[src:snmp/management-information-base] The top-level MIB OIDs belong to different standards organizations, while lower-level object IDs are allocated by associated organizations.
[src:snmp/management-information-base] This model permits management across all layers of the OSI reference model, extending into applications such as databases, email, and the Java reference model, as MIBs can be defined for all such area-specific information and operations.
[src:snmp/management-information-base] A managed object (sometimes called a MIB object or object) is one of any number of specific characteristics of a managed device.
[src:snmp/management-information-base] Managed objects are made up of one or more object instances, which are essentially variables.
[src:snmp/management-information-base] An OID uniquely identifies a managed object in the MIB hierarchy.
[src:snmp/management-information-base] An example of a managed object is *`atInput`*, which is a scalar object that contains a single object instance, the integer value that indicates the total number of input AppleTalk packets on a router interface.
[src:snmp/management-information-base] The first version of the Structure of Management Information (SMIv1) specifies the use of a number of SMI-specific data types, which are divided into two categories: simple data types and application-wide data types.
[src:snmp/management-information-base] The SNMPv1 SMI defines highly structured tables that are used to group the instances of a tabular object (that is, an object that contains multiple variables).
[src:snmp/management-information-base] Tables are composed of zero or more rows, which are indexed in a way that allows an SNMP manager to retrieve or alter an entire row with a single `Get`, `GetNext`, or `Set` command.
[src:snmp/management-information-base] The second version of the SMI (SMIv2) is described in RFC 2578 and RFC 2579.
[src:snmp/management-information-base] It enhances and adds to the SMIv1-specific data types, such as including bit strings, network addresses, and counters.
[src:snmp/management-information-base] Bit strings are defined only in SMIv2 and comprise zero or more named bits that specify a value.
[src:snmp/management-information-base] Network addresses represent an address from a particular protocol family.
[src:snmp/management-information-base] Counters are non-negative integers that increase until they reach a maximum value and then return to zero.
[src:snmp/management-information-base] In SMIv1, a 32-bit counter size is specified.
[src:snmp/management-information-base] In SMIv2, 32-bit and 64-bit counters are defined.
[src:snmp/management-information-base] SMIv2 also specifies information modules, which specify a group of related definitions.
[src:snmp/management-information-base] Three types of SMI information modules exist: MIB modules, compliance statements, and capability statements.
[src:snmp/management-information-base] MIB modules are occasionally updated to add new functionality, remove ambiguities and fix defects.
[src:snmp/management-information-base] These changes are made in conformance to section 10 of RFC 2578 and section 5 of RFC 2579.
[src:snmp/management-information-base] An example of a MIB module that has been updated many times is the important set of objects that was originally defined in RFC 1213, also known as "MIB-II".
[src:snmp/management-information-base] There are a large number of MIBs defined by standards organizations like the IETF, private enterprises and other entities.
[src:snmp/management-information-base] There are 318 RFCs in the first 5000 RFCs from the IETF that contain MIBs.
[src:snmp/management-information-base] The IETF and IEEE have agreed to move MIBs relating to IEEE work (for example, Ethernet and bridging) to their respective IEEE workgroup.
[src:snmp/management-information-base] This is in process and a few items are complete.
[src:snmp/object-identifier] In computing, **object identifiers** or **OIDs** are an identifier mechanism standardized by the International Telecommunication Union (ITU) and ISO/IEC for naming any object, concept, or "thing" with a globally unambiguous persistent name.
[src:snmp/object-identifier] An OID corresponds to a node in the "OID tree" or hierarchy, which is formally defined using the ITU's OID standard, X.660.
[src:snmp/object-identifier] Each node in the tree is represented by a series of integers separated by periods, corresponding to the path from the root through the series of ancestor nodes, to the node.
[src:snmp/object-identifier] Each node in the tree is controlled by an assigning authority, which may define child nodes under the node and delegate assigning authority for the child nodes.
[src:snmp/object-identifier] Continuing with the example, the node numbers under root node "1" are assigned by ISO; the nodes under "1.3.6" are assigned by the US Department of Defense; the nodes under "1.3.6.1.4.1" are assigned by IANA; the nodes under "1.3.6.1.4.1.343" are assigned by Intel Corporation, and so forth.
[src:snmp/object-identifier] There are multiple ways to acquire a OID.
[src:snmp/simple-network-management-protocol] SNMP is widely used in network management for network monitoring.
[src:snmp/simple-network-management-protocol] SNMP exposes management data in the form of variables on the managed systems organized in a management information base (MIB), which describes the system status and configuration.
[src:snmp/simple-network-management-protocol] These variables can then be remotely queried (and, in some circumstances, manipulated) by network management applications.
[src:snmp/simple-network-management-protocol] Three significant versions of SNMP have been developed and deployed.
[src:snmp/simple-network-management-protocol] SNMPv1 is the original version of the protocol.
[src:snmp/simple-network-management-protocol] More recent versions, SNMPv2c and SNMPv3, feature improvements in performance, flexibility and security.
[src:snmp/simple-network-management-protocol] SNMP is a component of the Internet Protocol Suite as defined by the Internet Engineering Task Force (IETF).
[src:snmp/simple-network-management-protocol] It consists of a set of standards for network management, including an application layer protocol, a database schema, and a set of data objects.
[src:snmp/simple-network-management-protocol] In typical uses of SNMP, one or more administrative computers called *managers* have the task of monitoring or managing a group of hosts or devices on a computer network.
[src:snmp/simple-network-management-protocol] Each managed system executes a software component called an *agent* that reports information via SNMP to the manager.
[src:snmp/simple-network-management-protocol] A *managed device* is a network node that implements an SNMP interface that allows unidirectional (read-only) or bidirectional (read and write) access to node-specific information.
[src:snmp/simple-network-management-protocol] Managed devices exchange node-specific information with the NMSs.
[src:snmp/simple-network-management-protocol] Sometimes called network elements, the managed devices can be any type of device, including, but not limited to, routers, access servers, switches, cable modems, bridges, hubs, IP telephones, IP video cameras, computer hosts, and printers.
[src:snmp/simple-network-management-protocol] An *agent* is a network-management software module that resides on a managed device.
[src:snmp/simple-network-management-protocol] An agent has local knowledge of management information and translates that information to or from an SNMP-specific form.
[src:snmp/simple-network-management-protocol] A *network management station* executes applications that monitor and control managed devices.
[src:snmp/simple-network-management-protocol] NMSs provide the bulk of the processing and memory resources required for network management.
[src:snmp/simple-network-management-protocol] One or more NMSs may exist on any managed network.
[src:snmp/simple-network-management-protocol] SNMP agents expose management data on the managed systems as variables.
[src:snmp/simple-network-management-protocol] The protocol also permits active management tasks, such as configuration changes, through remote modification of these variables.
[src:snmp/simple-network-management-protocol] The variables accessible via SNMP are organized in hierarchies.
[src:snmp/simple-network-management-protocol] SNMP itself does not define which variables a managed system should offer.
[src:snmp/simple-network-management-protocol] Rather, SNMP uses an extensible design that allows applications to define their own hierarchies.
[src:snmp/simple-network-management-protocol] These hierarchies are described as a management information base (MIB).
[src:snmp/simple-network-management-protocol] MIBs describe the structure of the management data of a device subsystem; they use a hierarchical namespace containing object identifiers (OID).
[src:snmp/simple-network-management-protocol] Each OID identifies a variable that can be read or set via SNMP.
[src:snmp/simple-network-management-protocol] MIBs use the notation defined by Structure of Management Information Version 2.0 (SMIv2, RFC 2578), a subset of ASN.1.
[src:snmp/simple-network-management-protocol] SNMP operates in the application layer of the Internet protocol suite.
[src:snmp/simple-network-management-protocol] All SNMP messages are transported via User Datagram Protocol (UDP).
[src:snmp/simple-network-management-protocol] The SNMP agent receives requests on UDP port 161.
[src:snmp/simple-network-management-protocol] The manager may send requests from any available source port to port 161 in the agent.
[src:snmp/simple-network-management-protocol] The agent response is sent back to the source port on the manager.
[src:snmp/simple-network-management-protocol] The manager receives notifications (*Traps* and *InformRequests*) on port 162.
[src:snmp/simple-network-management-protocol] The agent may generate notifications from any available port.
[src:snmp/simple-network-management-protocol] When used with Transport Layer Security or Datagram Transport Layer Security, requests are received on port 10161 and notifications are sent to port 10162.
[src:snmp/simple-network-management-protocol] SNMPv1 specifies five core protocol data units (PDUs).
[src:snmp/simple-network-management-protocol] Two other PDUs, *GetBulkRequest* and *InformRequest* were added in SNMPv2 and the *Report* PDU was added in SNMPv3.
[src:snmp/simple-network-management-protocol] A manager-to-agent request to retrieve the value of a variable or list of variables.
[src:snmp/simple-network-management-protocol] Desired variables are specified in variable bindings (the value field is not used).
[src:snmp/simple-network-management-protocol] A manager-to-agent request to change the value of a variable or list of variables.
[src:snmp/simple-network-management-protocol] Variable bindings are specified in the body of the request.
[src:snmp/simple-network-management-protocol] Changes to all specified variables are to be made as an atomic operation by the agent.
[src:snmp/simple-network-management-protocol] with (current) new values for the variables is returned.
[src:snmp/simple-network-management-protocol] A manager-to-agent request to discover available variables and their values.
[src:snmp/simple-network-management-protocol] Rows of a table can be read by specifying column OIDs in the variable bindings of the request.
[src:snmp/simple-network-management-protocol] with multiple variable bindings walked from the variable binding or bindings in the request.
[src:snmp/simple-network-management-protocol] fields are used to control response behavior.
[src:snmp/simple-network-management-protocol] Asynchronous notification from agent to manager.
[src:snmp/simple-network-management-protocol] While in other SNMP communication, the manager actively requests information from the agent, these are PDUs that are sent from the agent to the manager without being explicitly requested.
[src:snmp/simple-network-management-protocol] enable an agent to notify the management station of significant events by way of an unsolicited SNMP message.
[src:snmp/simple-network-management-protocol] value, an OID identifying the type of trap and optional variable bindings.
[src:snmp/simple-network-management-protocol] Destination addressing for traps is determined in an application-specific manner, typically through trap configuration variables in the MIB.
[src:snmp/simple-network-management-protocol] fixes this as an acknowledgement is returned on receipt.
[src:snmp/simple-network-management-protocol] RFC 1157 specifies that an SNMP implementation must accept a message of at least 484 bytes in length.
[src:snmp/simple-network-management-protocol] In practice, SNMP implementations accept longer messages.
[src:snmp/simple-network-management-protocol] If implemented correctly, an SNMP message is discarded if the decoding of the message fails and thus malformed SNMP requests are ignored.
[src:snmp/simple-network-management-protocol] A successfully decoded SNMP request is then authenticated using the community string.
[src:snmp/simple-network-management-protocol] If the authentication fails, a trap is generated indicating an authentication failure and the message is dropped.
[src:snmp/simple-network-management-protocol] SNMPv1 and SNMPv2c use *communities* to establish trust between managers and agents.
[src:snmp/simple-network-management-protocol] Most agents support three community names, one each for read-only, read-write and trap.
[src:snmp/simple-network-management-protocol] These three *community strings* control different types of activities.
[src:snmp/simple-network-management-protocol] The read-only community applies to *get* requests.
[src:snmp/simple-network-management-protocol] The read-write community string applies to *set* requests.
[src:snmp/simple-network-management-protocol] The trap community string applies to receipt of *traps*.
[src:snmp/simple-network-management-protocol] SNMPv3 also uses community strings, but allows for secure authentication and communication between SNMP manager and agent.
[src:snmp/simple-network-management-protocol] In practice, SNMP implementations often support multiple versions: typically SNMPv1, SNMPv2c, and SNMPv3.
[src:snmp/simple-network-management-protocol] SNMP version 1 (SNMPv1) is the initial implementation of the SNMP protocol.
[src:snmp/simple-network-management-protocol] The design of SNMPv1 was done in the 1980s by a group of collaborators who viewed the officially sponsored OSI/IETF/NSF (National Science Foundation) effort (HEMS/CMIS/CMIP) as both unimplementable in the computing platforms of the time as well as potentially unworkable.
[src:snmp/simple-network-management-protocol] SNMP was approved based on a belief that it was an interim protocol needed for taking steps towards large-scale deployment of the Internet and its commercialization.
[src:snmp/simple-network-management-protocol] SNMPv1 is widely used and is the de facto network management protocol in the Internet community.
[src:snmp/simple-network-management-protocol] SNMPv1 may be carried by transport layer protocols such as User Datagram Protocol (UDP), OSI Connectionless-mode Network Service (CLNS), AppleTalk Datagram Delivery Protocol (DDP), and Novell Internetwork Packet Exchange (IPX).
[src:snmp/simple-network-management-protocol] Version 1 has been criticized for its poor security.
[src:snmp/simple-network-management-protocol] For example, an organization may consider their internal network to be sufficiently secure that no encryption is necessary for its SNMP messages.
[src:snmp/simple-network-management-protocol] In such cases, the *community name*, which is transmitted in cleartext, tends to be viewed as a de facto password, in spite of the original specification.
[src:snmp/simple-network-management-protocol] SNMPv2, defined by RFC 1441 and RFC 1452, revises version 1 and includes improvements in the areas of performance, security and manager-to-manager communications.
[src:snmp/simple-network-management-protocol] It introduced *GetBulkRequest*, an alternative to iterative GetNextRequests for retrieving large amounts of management data in a single request.
[src:snmp/simple-network-management-protocol] The new party-based security system introduced in SNMPv2, viewed by many as overly complex, was not widely adopted.
[src:snmp/simple-network-management-protocol] This version of SNMP reached the Proposed Standard level of maturity, but was deemed obsolete by later versions.
[src:snmp/simple-network-management-protocol] SNMP version 2 introduces the option for 64-bit data counters.
[src:snmp/simple-network-management-protocol] Version 1 was designed only with 32-bit counters, which can store integer values from zero to 4.29 billion (precisely 4294967295).
[src:snmp/simple-network-management-protocol] A 32-bit version 1 counter cannot store the maximum speed of a 10-gigabit or larger interface, expressed in bits per second.
[src:snmp/simple-network-management-protocol] Similarly, a 32-bit counter tracking statistics for a 10-gigabit or larger interface can roll over back to zero again in less than one minute, which may be a shorter time interval than a counter is polled to read its current state.
[src:snmp/simple-network-management-protocol] This would result in lost or invalid data due to the undetected value rollover and corruption of trend-tracking data.
[src:snmp/simple-network-management-protocol] The 64-bit version 2 counter can store values from zero to 18.4 quintillion (precisely 18,446,744,073,709,551,615) and so is currently unlikely to experience a counter rollover between polling events.
[src:snmp/simple-network-management-protocol] For example, 1.6 terabit Ethernet is predicted to become available by 2025.
[src:snmp/simple-network-management-protocol] A 64-bit counter incrementing at a rate of 1.6 trillion bits per second would be able to retain information for such an interface without rolling over for 133 days.
[src:snmp/simple-network-management-protocol] SNMPv2c is incompatible with SNMPv1 in two key areas: message formats and protocol operations.
[src:snmp/simple-network-management-protocol] SNMPv2c messages use a different header and different protocol data unit (PDU) formats than SNMPv1 messages.
[src:snmp/simple-network-management-protocol] SNMPv2c also uses two protocol operations that are not specified in SNMPv1.
[src:snmp/simple-network-management-protocol] To overcome incompatibility, RFC 3584 defines two SNMPv1/v2c coexistence strategies: proxy agents and bilingual network-management systems.
[src:snmp/simple-network-management-protocol] An SNMPv2 agent can act as a proxy agent on behalf of SNMPv1-managed devices.
[src:snmp/simple-network-management-protocol] When an SNMPv2 NMS issues a command intended for an SNMPv1 agent, it sends it to the SNMPv2 proxy agent instead.
[src:snmp/simple-network-management-protocol] The proxy agent forwards `Get`, `GetNext`, and `Set` messages to the SNMPv1 agent unchanged.
[src:snmp/simple-network-management-protocol] `GetBulk` messages are converted by the proxy agent to `GetNext` messages and then are forwarded to the SNMPv1 agent.
[src:snmp/simple-network-management-protocol] Additionally, the proxy agent receives and maps SNMPv1 trap messages to SNMPv2 trap messages and then forwards them to the NMS.
[src:snmp/simple-network-management-protocol] Bilingual SNMPv2 network-management systems support both SNMPv1 and SNMPv2.
[src:snmp/simple-network-management-protocol] To support this dual-management environment, a management application examines information stored in a local database to determine whether the agent supports SNMPv1 or SNMPv2.
[src:snmp/simple-network-management-protocol] Based on the information in the database, the NMS communicates with the agent using the appropriate version of SNMP.
[src:snmp/simple-network-management-protocol] Although SNMPv3 makes no changes to the protocol aside from the addition of cryptographic security, it looks very different due to new textual conventions, concepts, and terminology.
[src:snmp/simple-network-management-protocol] The most visible change was to define a secure version of SNMP, by adding security and remote configuration enhancements to SNMP.
[src:snmp/simple-network-management-protocol] The security aspect is addressed by offering both strong authentication and data encryption for privacy.
[src:snmp/simple-network-management-protocol] For the administration aspect, SNMPv3 focuses on two parts, namely notification originators and proxy forwarders.
[src:snmp/simple-network-management-protocol] The changes also facilitate remote configuration and administration of the SNMP entities, as well as addressing issues related to the large-scale deployment, accounting, and fault management.
[src:snmp/simple-network-management-protocol] Security was one of the biggest weaknesses of SNMP until v3.
[src:snmp/simple-network-management-protocol] Authentication in SNMP Versions 1 and 2 amounts to nothing more than a password (community string) sent in clear text between a manager and agent.
[src:snmp/simple-network-management-protocol] Each SNMPv3 message contains security parameters that are encoded as an octet string.
[src:snmp/simple-network-management-protocol] The meaning of these security parameters depends on the security model being used.
[src:snmp/simple-network-management-protocol] v3 also defines the USM and VACM, which were later followed by a transport security model (TSM) that provided support for SNMPv3 over SSH and SNMPv3 over TLS and DTLS.
[src:snmp/simple-network-management-protocol] As of 2004 the IETF recognizes *Simple Network Management Protocol version 3* as defined by RFC 3411–RFC 3418 (also known as STD0062) as the current standard version of SNMP.
[src:snmp/simple-network-management-protocol] The IETF has designated SNMPv3 a full Internet standard, the highest maturity level for an RFC.
[src:snmp/simple-network-management-protocol] It considers earlier versions to be obsolete (designating them variously *Historic* or *Obsolete*).
[src:snmp/simple-network-management-protocol] Some SNMP values (especially tabular values) require specific knowledge of table indexing schemes, and these index values are not necessarily consistent across platforms.
[src:snmp/simple-network-management-protocol] Some major equipment vendors tend to over-extend their proprietary command line interface (CLI) centric configuration and control systems.
[src:snmp/simple-network-management-protocol] In February 2002 the Carnegie Mellon Software Engineering Institute (CM-SEI) Computer Emergency Response Team Coordination Center (CERT-CC) issued an Advisory on SNMPv1, after the Oulu University Secure Programming Group conducted a thorough analysis of SNMP message handling.
[src:snmp/simple-network-management-protocol] Most SNMP implementations, regardless of which version of the protocol they support, use the same program code for decoding protocol data units (PDU) and problems were identified in this code.
[src:snmp/simple-network-management-protocol] Other problems were found with decoding SNMP trap messages received by the SNMP management station or requests received by the SNMP agent on the network device.
[src:snmp/simple-network-management-protocol] Many vendors had to issue patches for their SNMP implementations.
[src:snmp/simple-network-management-protocol] Because SNMP is designed to allow administrators to monitor and configure network devices remotely, it can also be used to penetrate a network.
[src:snmp/simple-network-management-protocol] A significant number of software tools can scan the entire network using SNMP; therefore, mistakes in the configuration of the read-write mode can make a network susceptible to attacks.
[src:snmp/simple-network-management-protocol] In 2001, Cisco released information that indicated that, even in read-only mode, the SNMP implementation of Cisco IOS is vulnerable to certain denial of service attacks.
[src:snmp/simple-network-management-protocol] These security issues can be fixed through an IOS upgrade.
[src:snmp/simple-network-management-protocol] If SNMP is not used in a network, it should be disabled in network devices.
[src:snmp/simple-network-management-protocol] When configuring SNMP read-only mode, close attention should be paid to the configuration of the access control and from which IP addresses SNMP messages are accepted.
[src:snmp/simple-network-management-protocol] If the SNMP servers are identified by their IP addresses, SNMP is only allowed to respond to these IPs and SNMP messages from other IP addresses would be denied.
[src:snmp/simple-network-management-protocol] However, IP address spoofing remains a security concern.
[src:snmp/simple-network-management-protocol] SNMP is available in different versions, and each version has its own security issues.
[src:snmp/simple-network-management-protocol] SNMP v1 sends passwords in plaintext over the network.
[src:snmp/simple-network-management-protocol] Therefore, passwords can be read with packet sniffing.
[src:snmp/simple-network-management-protocol] SNMP v2 allows password hashing with MD5, but this has to be configured.
[src:snmp/simple-network-management-protocol] Virtually all network management software support SNMP v1, but not necessarily SNMP v2 or v3.
[src:snmp/simple-network-management-protocol] SNMP v2 was specifically developed to provide data security, that is authentication, privacy and authorization, but only SNMP version 2c gained the endorsement of the Internet Engineering Task Force (IETF), while versions 2u and 2* failed to gain IETF approval due to security issues.
[src:snmp/simple-network-management-protocol] SNMP v3 uses MD5, Secure Hash Algorithm (SHA) and keyed algorithms to offer protection against unauthorized data modification and spoofing attacks.
[src:snmp/simple-network-management-protocol] If a higher level of security is needed the Data Encryption Standard (DES) can be optionally used in the cipher block chaining mode.
[src:snmp/simple-network-management-protocol] SNMP v3 is implemented on Cisco IOS since release 12.0(3)T.
[src:snmp/simple-network-management-protocol] SNMPv3 may be subject to brute force and dictionary attacks for guessing the authentication keys, or encryption keys, if these keys are generated from short (weak) passwords or passwords that can be found in a dictionary.
[src:snmp/simple-network-management-protocol] SNMPv3 allows both providing random uniformly distributed cryptographic keys and generating cryptographic keys from a password supplied by the user.
[src:snmp/simple-network-management-protocol] The risk of guessing authentication strings from hash values transmitted over the network depends on the cryptographic hash function used and the length of the hash value.
[src:snmp/simple-network-management-protocol] SNMPv3 uses the HMAC-SHA-2 authentication protocol for the User-based Security Model (USM).
[src:snmp/simple-network-management-protocol] SNMP does not use a more secure challenge-handshake authentication protocol.
[src:snmp/simple-network-management-protocol] SNMPv3 (like other SNMP protocol versions) is a stateless protocol, and it has been designed with a minimal amount of interactions between the agent and the manager.
[src:snmp/simple-network-management-protocol] Thus introducing a challenge-response handshake for each command would impose a burden on the agent (and possibly on the network itself) that the protocol designers deemed excessive and unacceptable.
[src:snmp/simple-network-management-protocol] The security deficiencies of all SNMP versions can be mitigated by IPsec authentication and confidentiality mechanisms.
[src:snmp/simple-network-management-protocol] SNMP also may be carried securely over Datagram Transport Layer Security (DTLS).
[src:snmp/simple-network-management-protocol] Many SNMP implementations include a type of automatic discovery where a new network component, such as a switch or router, is discovered and polled automatically.
[src:snmp/simple-network-management-protocol] In SNMPv1 and SNMPv2c, this is done through a *community string* that is transmitted in clear-text to other devices.
[src:snmp/simple-network-management-protocol] Clear-text passwords are a significant security risk.
[src:snmp/simple-network-management-protocol] Once the community string is known outside the organization, it could become the target for an attack.
[src:snmp/simple-network-management-protocol] To alert administrators of other attempts to glean community strings, SNMP can be configured to pass community-name authentication failure traps.
[src:snmp/simple-network-management-protocol] If SNMPv2 is used, the issue can be avoided by enabling password encryption on the SNMP agents of network devices.
[src:snmp/simple-network-management-protocol] The common default configuration for community strings are "public" for read-only access and "private" for read-write.
[src:snmp/simple-network-management-protocol] Because of the well-known defaults, SNMP topped the list of the SANS Institute's Common Default Configuration Issues and was number ten on the SANS Top 10 Most Critical Internet Security Threats for the year 2000.
[src:snmp/simple-network-management-protocol] System and network administrators frequently do not change these configurations.
[src:snmp/simple-network-management-protocol] Whether it runs over TCP or UDP, SNMPv1 and v2 are vulnerable to IP spoofing attacks.
[src:snmp/simple-network-management-protocol] With spoofing, attackers may bypass device access lists in agents that are implemented to restrict SNMP access.
[src:snmp/simple-network-management-protocol] SNMPv3 security mechanisms, such as USM or TSM, can prevent spoofing attacks.
